RT: @jkapsis @shiokmeats 1/2 Re: climate impacts of farmed v wild shrimp, carbon footprint is largely a function of land-use change. Tropical mangroves are incredible carbon sinks; destroying them for shrimp pens that will produce for 5-10 years is the prime driver of carbon intensity.

RT: @jkapsis @shiokmeats 2/2 Re: climate impact of wild shrimp v other fish, carbon footprint for both is a function of fuel expended in harvest + processing + supply chain choices. Lowest mass-market CO2 intensity is an abundant fishery (efficient catch) + frozen at sea + frozen freight.

RT: @jkapsis @shiokmeats 3/3 A meal of farmed shrimp has about the same carbon footprint as driving a gas car from California to Kansas. 

And farmed shrimp is often contaminated with antibiotics. And bacteria. And heavy metals. Never again!

https://t.co/JsBzZJDYfB

RT: @jkapsis @shiokmeats 2/3 Approximate carbon footprints (kg COe/ kg unfinished meat) from peer-reviewed lit:

US feedlot beef: 20
Amazon deforestation beef: 700
Former mangrove shrimp: 2000 

You can get particular with assumptions regarding finishing, farm size, etc, but the punch line is clear:

RT: @jkapsis @shiokmeats 1/3 Yes. A research team at Oregon State estimates that shrimp farmed on the site of former mangroves is 10x the CO2e/kg of beef from pastures in the deforested Amazon: https://t.co/lBmklNQQAK 

These OSU estimates are unpublished, so we also looked at peer-reviewed findings.

RT: One life lesson I've learned in investment diligence: I'm never eating farmed shrimp again. üç§ Shrimp farmed in former mangroves is far more carbon-intensive than even beef from slash & burn ag.
